# structure of an HTML document
An HTML document is structured with the following essential elements:

<!DOCTYPE html>: Declares the document type as HTML5.
<html>: The root element that contains all other HTML elements.
<head>: Contains meta-information about the document, like title, character set, and description.
<body>: Contains the content that is displayed on the webpage.

    ## Core HTML5 Elements
Headings: <h1>, <h2>, <h3>, etc., are used to define different levels of headings. <h1> is the most important.

    <h1>This is a Heading</h1>

    Paragraphs: <p> defines text in paragraph form.

        <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>

        Lists: <ul> defines an unordered list, and <ol> defines an ordered list. Both use <li> to define list items

            <ul>
                <li>Item 1</li>
                <li>Item 2</li>
            </ul>

            Links: <a> defines a hyperlink. The href attribute specifies the URL.

                <a href="https://www.example.com">Visit Example</a>

                Images: <img> embeds an image. The src attribute defines the image source, and alt provides alternative text.

                <img src="image.jpg" alt="A descriptive image">

                2. Semantic HTML
Semantic Tags
Semantic HTML tags describe the meaning of content on the web page, making it easier for both humans and machines to understand the structure and improve SEO.

<header>: Represents the header section of a webpage (often containing logos, navigation, etc.).

<footer>: Represents the footer section of a webpage (often containing contact info, copyright, etc.).

<nav>: Defines a section for navigation links.

<section>: Represents a distinct section of content (like an article or a part of the page).

<article>: Represents a self-contained piece of content, such as a blog post or news article.

    <header>
        <h1>Welcome to My Website</h1>
    </header>
    
    <main>
        <section>
            <h2>About Us</h2>
            <p>Information about the company.</p>
        </section>
    </main>
    
    <footer>
        <p>&copy; 2024 My Website. All rights reserved.</p>
    </footer>

    3. Accessibility and SEO Basics
Importance of Accessible HTML
Accessible HTML ensures that websites can be used by everyone, including people with disabilities. It improves user experience for those using screen readers or other assistive technologies.

alt Attribute for Images: The alt attribute provides a textual description of an image for screen readers.

<img src="logo.png" alt="Website Logo">

Accessible Links: Links should have meaningful text to describe the destination.

<a href="https://www.example.com">Visit our website</a>

SEO (Search Engine Optimization) Basics
SEO helps your content rank better in search engine results. HTML5 provides several tools to improve SEO:

<title> Tag: Specifies the title of the page, which appears in search engine results.

    <title>My Awesome Website</title>


